Other nerves have different relationships to the cubital fossa. Lateral to the cubital fossa, identify the radial nerve between the brachialis and the brachioradialis. Identify the ulnar nerve passing posterior to the medial epicondyle.  
Superficial to the cubital fossa, and removed in the preparation of this specimen, is deep fascia, superficial fascia and skin. In the superficial fascia is located the median cubital vein, which is a venous anastomosis between the cephalic and basilic veins. It is a common site for phlebotomy.

borders of the cubital fossa: its base is an imaginary line between the medial and lateral epicondyles, its lateral border is a muscle arising superior to the lateral epicondyle, the brachioradialis, and its medial border is a muscle arising from the medial epicondyle, the pronator teres. Identify, in the cubital fossa, from lateral to medial, the tendon of the biceps brachii, the brachial artery and the median nerve.
